WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.482 --> 00:00:05.480
ANDY: Hey, Austin.

00:00:05.480 --> 00:00:09.670
Today we have an
author, magician,

00:00:09.670 --> 00:00:11.710
host of "Scam School,"
the only show dedicated

00:00:11.710 --> 00:00:13.990
to social engineering at
the bar and on the street,

00:00:13.990 --> 00:00:17.730
and now "Hacking the System"
on the National Geographic

00:00:17.730 --> 00:00:18.230
Channel.

00:00:18.230 --> 00:00:19.771
Let's give a big,
warm Google awesome

00:00:19.771 --> 00:00:21.010
welcome to Brian Brushwood.

00:00:21.010 --> 00:00:21.760
[AUDIENCE  CHEERS]

00:00:21.760 --> 00:00:22.850
BRIAN BUSHWOOD: All right!

00:00:22.850 --> 00:00:24.414
Wow!

00:00:24.414 --> 00:00:25.080
What a response!

00:00:30.660 --> 00:00:32.840
Howdy guys, my name
is Brian Brushwood.

00:00:32.840 --> 00:00:34.590
Real quick, hands in
the air if any of you

00:00:34.590 --> 00:00:36.930
guys have seen any of the
projects that I've done.

00:00:36.930 --> 00:00:37.430
OK, great.

00:00:37.430 --> 00:00:38.750
This is great.

00:00:38.750 --> 00:00:42.045
Five years ago when somebody
asked who I was and what I did,

00:00:42.045 --> 00:00:43.230
it was very, very simple.

00:00:43.230 --> 00:00:45.710
My job is I am a
touring full-time stage

00:00:45.710 --> 00:00:48.270
performer who dabbles on
the internet here and there.

00:00:48.270 --> 00:00:50.450
Things have changed over
the last half decade.

00:00:50.450 --> 00:00:53.260
Nowadays I host a show
on National Geographic.

00:00:53.260 --> 00:00:56.120
You know, "Scam Schools," one
of the top 1,000 most subscribed

00:00:56.120 --> 00:00:58.490
channels on all of YouTube.

00:00:58.490 --> 00:01:02.110
But I wanted to talk about
where everything began.

00:01:02.110 --> 00:01:03.880
And where it began
was right here.

00:01:03.880 --> 00:01:06.800
This is a photo of me
and the Magician Teller

00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:10.220
from Penn and Teller, standing
on the exact spot where

00:01:10.220 --> 00:01:15.080
20 years before I originally
started street performing.

00:01:15.080 --> 00:01:17.500
At the age of 19,
20 years old, I

00:01:17.500 --> 00:01:20.400
had a vague sense that I wanted
to be like Penn and Teller.

00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:22.220
I wanted to be like
Harry Anderson.

00:01:22.220 --> 00:01:24.990
I wanted to be a travelling,
touring stage performer.

00:01:24.990 --> 00:01:26.750
But no sense of
how to get there.

00:01:26.750 --> 00:01:30.019
And so instead I
met Penn and Teller

00:01:30.019 --> 00:01:31.060
after one of their shows.

00:01:31.060 --> 00:01:32.302
They're very approachable.

00:01:32.302 --> 00:01:33.760
I encourage you to
watch their show

00:01:33.760 --> 00:01:35.790
and go up and meet
with them afterwards.

00:01:35.790 --> 00:01:39.261
And I made the joke
to Teller, I said hey,

00:01:39.261 --> 00:01:40.260
you know sign this card.

00:01:40.260 --> 00:01:41.791
Make it out to my bastard son.

00:01:41.791 --> 00:01:43.290
And he thought that
was funny enough

00:01:43.290 --> 00:01:45.399
that we struck up a
brief conversation,

00:01:45.399 --> 00:01:46.940
and I found out
later that I had been

00:01:46.940 --> 00:01:48.640
added on to his email list.

00:01:48.640 --> 00:01:51.390
And so I said, oh my gosh I
have Teller's email address.

00:01:51.390 --> 00:01:54.010
Of course, this is the mid
'90s and the very novelty

00:01:54.010 --> 00:01:56.230
of the e-mail was exciting.

00:01:56.230 --> 00:02:00.390
And four times I started to
write a letter to my hero,

00:02:00.390 --> 00:02:02.180
and I couldn't figure
out how to begin.

00:02:02.180 --> 00:02:04.222
I didn't want to sound
like just another fan.

00:02:04.222 --> 00:02:06.430
I assumed that he gets emails
like this all the time.

00:02:06.430 --> 00:02:07.346
I wanted to stand out.

00:02:07.346 --> 00:02:10.520
I wanted to get real
advice from him.

00:02:10.520 --> 00:02:14.160
And then one day, in
a fit of random rage,

00:02:14.160 --> 00:02:18.200
I wrote this, with the
subject heading of "Fury."

00:02:18.200 --> 00:02:20.500
And I wrote a letter
to Teller talking

00:02:20.500 --> 00:02:23.260
about how angry I was at him.

00:02:23.260 --> 00:02:24.740
Not for being brilliant.

00:02:24.740 --> 00:02:26.140
Not for being original.

00:02:26.140 --> 00:02:28.030
Not for being extraordinary.

00:02:28.030 --> 00:02:30.129
But because he got there first.

00:02:30.129 --> 00:02:32.670
And I realized that because he
got there first, I could never

00:02:32.670 --> 00:02:34.660
be the kind of
magician I wanted to be

00:02:34.660 --> 00:02:37.300
without looking like a shabby
Penn and Teller knockoff.

00:02:37.300 --> 00:02:40.890
One of the bits of advice that
I'd read from them in a article

00:02:40.890 --> 00:02:43.690
in I want to say "Genii
Magazinee," they say

00:02:43.690 --> 00:02:47.460
don't, when you are
writing your material,

00:02:47.460 --> 00:02:49.880
don't be inspired by
something you love.

00:02:49.880 --> 00:02:52.260
If you are inspired by
something that you love,

00:02:52.260 --> 00:02:55.170
the best you will be is
a pale, shabby imitation

00:02:55.170 --> 00:02:56.580
of whatever that thing is.

00:02:56.580 --> 00:02:59.690
So instead, be inspired
by what you hate.

00:02:59.690 --> 00:03:02.190
Go see a bunch of
crappy magic shows.

00:03:02.190 --> 00:03:04.860
Figure out exactly what
you hate about all of them

00:03:04.860 --> 00:03:06.860
and then be the exact opposite.

00:03:06.860 --> 00:03:10.320
Now you are something truly
original and extraordinary,

00:03:10.320 --> 00:03:13.200
and you made your own
space in the universe.

00:03:13.200 --> 00:03:16.760
So I wrote him, I don't know
just to give him a hard time.

00:03:16.760 --> 00:03:18.880
And writing the
email was cathartic.

00:03:18.880 --> 00:03:19.942
I felt this weight off.

00:03:19.942 --> 00:03:21.150
I was like, whoa, look at me.

00:03:21.150 --> 00:03:23.460
I feel like I
expressed by my rage.

00:03:23.460 --> 00:03:24.430
I'm 19.

00:03:24.430 --> 00:03:28.360
And the next morning,
to my utter surprise,

00:03:28.360 --> 00:03:33.280
Teller wrote a four and
half page essay in response

00:03:33.280 --> 00:03:34.650
on the nature of creativity.

00:03:34.650 --> 00:03:37.420
By the way, just look at
Brian Brushwood Teller letter

00:03:37.420 --> 00:03:39.440
if you want to read
the entire thing.

00:03:39.440 --> 00:03:42.882
And in it he talks about--
there's one line that

00:03:42.882 --> 00:03:44.090
really sticks out in my mind.

00:03:44.090 --> 00:03:47.260
He says, take your best
stab and keep on stabbing.

00:03:47.260 --> 00:03:49.100
If it's in you it's
going to come out.

00:03:49.100 --> 00:03:51.590
And what I took
away from that is

00:03:51.590 --> 00:03:53.440
that I needed to put
myself in a position

00:03:53.440 --> 00:03:55.250
to discover what was inside me.

00:03:55.250 --> 00:03:59.250
And what I discovered is
that street performing seemed

00:03:59.250 --> 00:04:01.000
like a good place to begin.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:03.205
It's something that
nobody could tell you no.

00:04:03.205 --> 00:04:04.580
The worst case
scenario is people

00:04:04.580 --> 00:04:05.752
turn around and walk away.

00:04:05.752 --> 00:04:07.960
And if you're really lucky,
you get $50 of beer money

00:04:07.960 --> 00:04:09.190
by the end of the night.

00:04:09.190 --> 00:04:11.110
Unfortunately,
here in Austin they

00:04:11.110 --> 00:04:14.540
don't have an established
hierarchy or permitting

00:04:14.540 --> 00:04:17.010
system for street performing,
or they didn't at the time.

00:04:17.010 --> 00:04:21.029
And so I actually noticed
that this souvenir

00:04:21.029 --> 00:04:23.985
shop on Sixth street has
a two foot wide strip.

00:04:23.985 --> 00:04:25.360
It used to be a
jewelry shop that

00:04:25.360 --> 00:04:26.700
would close in the evenings.

00:04:26.700 --> 00:04:30.550
And I figured out that if I
was on the public sidewalk,

00:04:30.550 --> 00:04:32.990
I was illegally performing
without a permit.

00:04:32.990 --> 00:04:37.370
But if I was on this two foot
strip, I was only trespassing.

00:04:37.370 --> 00:04:39.042
And if I was only
trespassing, then

00:04:39.042 --> 00:04:41.500
they could only chase me off
if it was the private property

00:04:41.500 --> 00:04:43.416
owners, or at least
that's what I told myself.

00:04:43.416 --> 00:04:47.770
And over this time, I
learned a bit about-- eh--

00:04:47.770 --> 00:04:49.330
when you put yourself
out there, when

00:04:49.330 --> 00:04:51.620
you try to share what's in
your heart, when you try

00:04:51.620 --> 00:04:54.599
to have some kind
of art out there,

00:04:54.599 --> 00:04:57.140
turns out you're going to deal
with people who don't like it.

00:04:57.140 --> 00:04:59.140
And if there's one thing
I want you to take away

00:04:59.140 --> 00:05:02.260
from the opening
remarks here is that you

00:05:02.260 --> 00:05:03.620
should love your trolls.

00:05:03.620 --> 00:05:06.280
I started off not
loving my trolls.

00:05:06.280 --> 00:05:08.090
I learned when I was
street performing

00:05:08.090 --> 00:05:11.100
that the way you get
someone to shut the hell up

00:05:11.100 --> 00:05:14.500
is shine just enough
spotlight on them that they

00:05:14.500 --> 00:05:18.350
feel a fraction of the fear
that I feel on stage performing.

00:05:18.350 --> 00:05:20.790
I realized that if
I wanted to keep

00:05:20.790 --> 00:05:22.650
going with my narrative,
what I needed to do

00:05:22.650 --> 00:05:26.250
was turn the entire rest of
the audience against that one

00:05:26.250 --> 00:05:27.530
person.

00:05:27.530 --> 00:05:29.720
And you learn zingers.

00:05:29.720 --> 00:05:31.880
In many ways, doing any
kind of variety performer

00:05:31.880 --> 00:05:35.570
is like living the life
of "Groundhog Day."

00:05:35.570 --> 00:05:36.870
You do the same show.

00:05:36.870 --> 00:05:40.190
It doesn't matter where you
are, what situation you're in,

00:05:40.190 --> 00:05:43.700
for that one hour, it's
always the same strict stage.

00:05:43.700 --> 00:05:45.200
It's always the same audience.

00:05:45.200 --> 00:05:46.760
It's always the same situations.

00:05:46.760 --> 00:05:50.100
Whenever you see a seasoned
variety performer have

00:05:50.100 --> 00:05:52.730
a quick zinger, it
is not because they

00:05:52.730 --> 00:05:54.180
are very quick on their feet.

00:05:54.180 --> 00:05:56.670
The reason was, three years
ago someone heckled him

00:05:56.670 --> 00:05:59.290
with the exact same line,
and four days afterwards, he

00:05:59.290 --> 00:06:00.550
was like, son of a bitch!

00:06:00.550 --> 00:06:01.760
That's what I should've said!

00:06:01.760 --> 00:06:03.830
And he filed it away, right?

00:06:03.830 --> 00:06:05.090
And it's very comforting.

00:06:05.090 --> 00:06:07.630
It's very soothing
to have this idea

00:06:07.630 --> 00:06:09.890
that no matter how
bad one show goes,

00:06:09.890 --> 00:06:14.290
you know that down the
road you can try again.

00:06:14.290 --> 00:06:17.840
So after performing on the
street for a little bit,

00:06:17.840 --> 00:06:20.087
I moved indoors, and
I started performing

00:06:20.087 --> 00:06:22.170
at a little venue called
the Electric Lounge where

00:06:22.170 --> 00:06:25.500
I would do the same 15 minute
set and then pass the hat.

00:06:25.500 --> 00:06:29.320
And I started touring
to colleges nationwide.

00:06:29.320 --> 00:06:33.100
And I had a moment-- some
lessons come to you early on.

00:06:33.100 --> 00:06:35.510
You have an idea for what
kind of outrageous stunt

00:06:35.510 --> 00:06:36.500
you want to pull.

00:06:36.500 --> 00:06:40.240
And then other things
take longer to realize.

00:06:40.240 --> 00:06:43.680
And in this case, I
was at Davis and Elkins

00:06:43.680 --> 00:06:48.260
college in West
Virginia, and I did not

00:06:48.260 --> 00:06:49.900
connect with that audience.

00:06:49.900 --> 00:06:54.610
My show was meant to be a
sarcastic, almost middle finger

00:06:54.610 --> 00:06:58.770
parody of, what at the
time was the bedazzled,

00:06:58.770 --> 00:07:03.620
sequined-wearing, fans blowing
your David Copperfield hair

00:07:03.620 --> 00:07:04.920
kind of magic show.

00:07:04.920 --> 00:07:07.590
And it turns out that the
exact thing I was mocking

00:07:07.590 --> 00:07:09.810
was what that crowd
really wanted to see.

00:07:09.810 --> 00:07:14.120
And at the end of the show, I
walked off stage and somebody

00:07:14.120 --> 00:07:16.520
threw fruit at my stage.

00:07:16.520 --> 00:07:18.620
I did not know that
this was a real thing.

00:07:18.620 --> 00:07:21.840
I walk off, and all of a
sudden there's just a slam,

00:07:21.840 --> 00:07:23.690
and I turn around
just in time to see

00:07:23.690 --> 00:07:28.320
orange juice you know sliming
down over one of my props.

00:07:28.320 --> 00:07:30.560
And it occurred to
me, I was like, why

00:07:30.560 --> 00:07:33.190
is it that I'm not connecting
with this audience?

00:07:33.190 --> 00:07:35.140
And then this happened.

00:07:35.140 --> 00:07:38.210
This is a statement that I never
thought I was going to make.

00:07:38.210 --> 00:07:43.140
Later, the next year, I toured
with Brooks and Dunn, Rascal

00:07:43.140 --> 00:07:46.830
Flatts, and Brad Paisley is a
thing that actually happened.

00:07:46.830 --> 00:07:49.750
And they set up something
called the Neon Circus Stage.

00:07:49.750 --> 00:07:53.080
It was like a midway, and I
would do my punk rock magic.

00:07:53.080 --> 00:07:55.430
I would shove tubes up my
nose, pull it out my mouth,

00:07:55.430 --> 00:07:57.570
I would hammer a 4 and
1/2 inch nail in my nose

00:07:57.570 --> 00:07:59.340
and have blood and
guts everywhere.

00:07:59.340 --> 00:08:01.710
But one of the best things
that came out of all this

00:08:01.710 --> 00:08:03.410
was a-- we had our own tour bus.

00:08:03.410 --> 00:08:04.700
It was amazing.

00:08:04.700 --> 00:08:06.470
That's me giving the
middle finger, sorry.

00:08:06.470 --> 00:08:07.800
Straight jacket escape.

00:08:07.800 --> 00:08:09.330
This guy right here.

00:08:09.330 --> 00:08:11.280
His name is Dennis Rogers.

00:08:11.280 --> 00:08:15.770
And he, at the time I
thought was so, so, so wrong.

00:08:15.770 --> 00:08:18.960
Dennis Rogers is a
former world champion arm

00:08:18.960 --> 00:08:21.270
wrestler who has
a supreme gift, he

00:08:21.270 --> 00:08:23.930
has unbelievably
dense muscle tissue.

00:08:23.930 --> 00:08:27.690
If you touch his forearm,
it is like touching a brick.

00:08:27.690 --> 00:08:31.190
His act consists of stuff
like taking a frying pan

00:08:31.190 --> 00:08:33.250
and rolling it up like
he's rolling a newspaper.

00:08:33.250 --> 00:08:35.370
He'll take a wrench,
you know, that you'll

00:08:35.370 --> 00:08:37.809
do your best to
even make a dent in,

00:08:37.809 --> 00:08:39.520
and he just bends it
like it's nothing.

00:08:39.520 --> 00:08:41.059
He bends iron spikes.

00:08:41.059 --> 00:08:45.210
He is legitimately,
phenomenally gifted in strength.

00:08:45.210 --> 00:08:48.134
And yet I saw him
in this environment,

00:08:48.134 --> 00:08:49.800
where you get a bunch
of people-- that's

00:08:49.800 --> 00:08:52.690
the nice thing about street
performing or midway performing

00:08:52.690 --> 00:08:55.019
is that it's the most
artistically pure venue I

00:08:55.019 --> 00:08:55.560
can think of.

00:08:55.560 --> 00:08:57.947
Because nobody's
there to see you.

00:08:57.947 --> 00:08:59.530
Nobody showed up
because you're there.

00:08:59.530 --> 00:09:04.170
You have to earn the respect to
get people to stop and watch.

00:09:04.170 --> 00:09:08.060
And there was one show
that it drove me nuts,

00:09:08.060 --> 00:09:10.000
because I'm watching
Dennis Rogers, who

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:13.460
again is legitimately the best
in breed with what he does.

00:09:13.460 --> 00:09:17.460
And I watch him
responding, giving power

00:09:17.460 --> 00:09:20.990
to these trolls, these hecklers.

00:09:20.990 --> 00:09:24.720
There's three or four of these
frat boy douchebags sitting

00:09:24.720 --> 00:09:27.860
there with their red Solo cups
shouting out that this is fake,

00:09:27.860 --> 00:09:30.010
or that's rigged, or whatever.

00:09:30.010 --> 00:09:34.090
And to me, as the jaded, bitter
street performer, I'm like,

00:09:34.090 --> 00:09:36.660
look you mock them, turn
the audience against them,

00:09:36.660 --> 00:09:38.560
look them in the
eye, say shut up,

00:09:38.560 --> 00:09:40.260
and then you get
on with your show.

00:09:40.260 --> 00:09:42.220
And instead, what
I watched Dennis

00:09:42.220 --> 00:09:44.370
do was give them all the power.

00:09:44.370 --> 00:09:47.450
He came up afterward-- he did
his whole show twice, once

00:09:47.450 --> 00:09:50.280
on stage and again
one-on-one for them, handing

00:09:50.280 --> 00:09:51.940
over the individual wrenches.

00:09:51.940 --> 00:09:53.940
Well, here go ahead and
check out the wrench.

00:09:53.940 --> 00:09:54.680
Try to bend it.

00:09:54.680 --> 00:09:55.875
And then [SOUND EFFECT].

00:09:55.875 --> 00:09:58.270
Oh, sure, yeah, I'll be
happy to arm wrestle you.

00:09:58.270 --> 00:10:01.170
By the way, I'm genuinely a
world champion arm wrestler.

00:10:01.170 --> 00:10:05.160
And at the time, I
was so disappointed

00:10:05.160 --> 00:10:07.240
because I felt like, ah,
Dennis don't you get it?

00:10:07.240 --> 00:10:07.900
They're cattle.

00:10:07.900 --> 00:10:10.030
They need to be moved
to the slaughter chutes.

00:10:10.030 --> 00:10:11.450
You need to own
this performance.

00:10:11.450 --> 00:10:13.400
You're better than that.

00:10:13.400 --> 00:10:17.070
And it turns out that
I was completely wrong,

00:10:17.070 --> 00:10:19.420
and Dennis is 100% right.

00:10:19.420 --> 00:10:23.810
Because, after touring for
15 years with the stage show,

00:10:23.810 --> 00:10:25.920
and getting pretty
good at it, it

00:10:25.920 --> 00:10:29.270
turns out that all
the rules changed once

00:10:29.270 --> 00:10:30.480
we launched "Scam School."

00:10:30.480 --> 00:10:32.630
We launched "Scam
School" back in 2008.

00:10:32.630 --> 00:10:36.620
And I thought, at the
time, that "Scam School"

00:10:36.620 --> 00:10:40.450
would be a good first practice
round before I got a real TV

00:10:40.450 --> 00:10:41.810
show, whatever that means.

00:10:41.810 --> 00:10:46.290
I thought that a simple show
about bar tricks and scams

00:10:46.290 --> 00:10:47.530
would be popular enough.

00:10:47.530 --> 00:10:50.420
And this will fold, like all
startups are going to fold,

00:10:50.420 --> 00:10:51.470
and who cares?

00:10:51.470 --> 00:10:54.960
And it turns out that here we
are seven, eight years later

00:10:54.960 --> 00:10:57.210
And one and a quarter
million subscribers.

00:10:57.210 --> 00:11:00.760
Specifically, when "Scam School"
launched, for the first time

00:11:00.760 --> 00:11:02.780
I got a new kind of heckler.

00:11:02.780 --> 00:11:05.690
I encountered the troll.

00:11:05.690 --> 00:11:07.841
This was, by the way,
all of the comments

00:11:07.841 --> 00:11:10.090
I grabbed-- I don't know if
you can read any of these,

00:11:10.090 --> 00:11:12.420
but I grabbed all of
these this morning.

00:11:12.420 --> 00:11:16.260
And they're all taking a dump
on my hairstyle at the time.

00:11:16.260 --> 00:11:19.010
Whatever.

00:11:19.010 --> 00:11:20.870
All of a sudden I
realized the rules

00:11:20.870 --> 00:11:23.680
that worked in a live
stage performance

00:11:23.680 --> 00:11:25.740
don't work for trolls.

00:11:25.740 --> 00:11:27.500
You can't shine a
spotlight on them

00:11:27.500 --> 00:11:29.680
because that's all
they want in the world.

00:11:29.680 --> 00:11:32.010
You can't turn the
audience against them

00:11:32.010 --> 00:11:34.590
because they don't care
what everyone else says.

00:11:34.590 --> 00:11:36.680
They are doing it
for the sheer joy of,

00:11:36.680 --> 00:11:39.610
in their mind speaking
truth to power, or whatever.

00:11:39.610 --> 00:11:43.820
And I went through a number of
phases in dealing with trolls.

00:11:43.820 --> 00:11:46.880
There was times I was
defensive, I was argumentative.

00:11:46.880 --> 00:11:50.210
For a good year my
reply to everyone

00:11:50.210 --> 00:11:54.340
was just to respond with
a link to the Big Lebowski

00:11:54.340 --> 00:11:56.180
with The Dude
saying, "Yeah, well,

00:11:56.180 --> 00:12:00.250
that's just your opinion, man."

00:12:00.250 --> 00:12:03.000
But ultimately, I found
myself in the position

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:06.210
that nowadays, when I respond,
if there's a pat answer,

00:12:06.210 --> 00:12:12.290
it's with an emoticon,
an Emoji saying, "Hugs.

00:12:12.290 --> 00:12:13.030
Come on over.

00:12:13.030 --> 00:12:14.080
Hey, check this out.

00:12:14.080 --> 00:12:16.080
You'll find out I'm an OK guy."

00:12:16.080 --> 00:12:18.730
And that seems to be the
most successful thing.

00:12:18.730 --> 00:12:21.110
Specifically, and
again, I don't know why,

00:12:21.110 --> 00:12:24.250
but it seems like taking
that Dennis Rogers'

00:12:24.250 --> 00:12:30.140
approach of respecting the
troll somehow pivots them.

00:12:30.140 --> 00:12:31.359
It flips them over.

00:12:31.359 --> 00:12:32.900
And I think about
it in terms-- there

00:12:32.900 --> 00:12:35.310
was a speaker in
the college market,

00:12:35.310 --> 00:12:37.300
and I wish I could
remember his name.

00:12:37.300 --> 00:12:39.640
But he told me Bruce
Lee never, ever

00:12:39.640 --> 00:12:41.320
tried to match force with force.

00:12:41.320 --> 00:12:43.430
When a punch was coming,
he never grabbed it.

00:12:43.430 --> 00:12:45.610
He would always divert
it off to the side.

00:12:45.610 --> 00:12:47.470
And that's what you
get with trolls.

00:12:47.470 --> 00:12:51.240
You don't worry about
when the wind is blowing

00:12:51.240 --> 00:12:53.060
the wrong direction,
if you're trying

00:12:53.060 --> 00:12:54.720
to get across the Atlantic.

00:12:54.720 --> 00:12:57.340
You worry when there is no wind.

00:12:57.340 --> 00:13:00.860
And the same energy that makes
trolls passionate to just

00:13:00.860 --> 00:13:06.000
scream, "I hate your hair!"
is the exact same thing that

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:09.020
by being recognised and
listen to it can be pivoted

00:13:09.020 --> 00:13:11.600
into making them one
of your biggest fans.

00:13:11.600 --> 00:13:14.170
And that is exactly what
happened with Dennis Rogers

00:13:14.170 --> 00:13:17.610
and those fraternity boys.

00:13:17.610 --> 00:13:20.290
And specifically-- so
one of the things that

00:13:20.290 --> 00:13:23.334
happened when I started
street performing is--

00:13:23.334 --> 00:13:24.750
the whole reason
I got started was

00:13:24.750 --> 00:13:27.840
because I knew that I
did not have the ability,

00:13:27.840 --> 00:13:31.960
I did not have the experience
to be clever on the fly,

00:13:31.960 --> 00:13:34.290
to wrap people in,
to build a crowd,

00:13:34.290 --> 00:13:35.830
to establish a connection.

00:13:35.830 --> 00:13:39.590
And so I needed a safe place
to be bad for me to be good.

00:13:39.590 --> 00:13:42.130
And the street was
perfect for that.

00:13:42.130 --> 00:13:44.090
I realized that when
"Scam School" launched,

00:13:44.090 --> 00:13:45.120
I didn't have the tools.

00:13:45.120 --> 00:13:47.450
I don't know how to deal
with this new type of trolls.

00:13:47.450 --> 00:13:50.837
And I wanted a passionate
fun-run community.

00:13:50.837 --> 00:13:53.420
And there was no way I was going
to get that five minutes once

00:13:53.420 --> 00:13:55.730
a week in a one
way conversation.

00:13:55.730 --> 00:13:57.992
So I turned on a
web camera, and I

00:13:57.992 --> 00:13:59.450
did something I
called the "BB Live

00:13:59.450 --> 00:14:00.890
Show," for Brian Brushwood.

00:14:00.890 --> 00:14:02.780
B.B. That's my initials.

00:14:02.780 --> 00:14:05.720
And it was genuinely awful.

00:14:05.720 --> 00:14:08.020
I go back, and I look at
it now, and it's miserable.

00:14:08.020 --> 00:14:08.630
It's awkward.

00:14:08.630 --> 00:14:10.600
I cringe.

00:14:10.600 --> 00:14:11.522
I'm fidgety.

00:14:11.522 --> 00:14:12.730
I don't have anything to say.

00:14:12.730 --> 00:14:14.100
It goes nowhere.

00:14:14.100 --> 00:14:16.320
And yet it was a
safe place to be bad.

00:14:16.320 --> 00:14:18.870
Because I could be bad
for 80 people at a time.

00:14:18.870 --> 00:14:20.620
That's the great thing
about the internet.

00:14:20.620 --> 00:14:21.820
One of two things happens.

00:14:21.820 --> 00:14:24.890
If you're spectacularly bad,
and you get famous for it,

00:14:24.890 --> 00:14:26.030
in which case, win.

00:14:26.030 --> 00:14:28.960
Or you're boring, in
which case nobody watches.

00:14:28.960 --> 00:14:30.002
In which case, win.

00:14:30.002 --> 00:14:31.460
Because you've got
that experience.

00:14:31.460 --> 00:14:33.330
You've got that training.

00:14:33.330 --> 00:14:35.660
Nowadays, that
community has become

00:14:35.660 --> 00:14:38.785
this fully self-sustained
community at diamondclub.tv.

00:14:41.810 --> 00:14:44.090
We've got five different
channels that are running.

00:14:44.090 --> 00:14:46.540
People are providing their
own gameplay content.

00:14:46.540 --> 00:14:49.710
There is a living chat room
that's alive at all times.

00:14:49.710 --> 00:14:53.390
And all of this began because
I found a safe place to be bad.

00:14:53.390 --> 00:14:55.330
So whatever your
artistic endeavor,

00:14:55.330 --> 00:14:59.349
I would say find a safe place
to be bad so you can be good.

00:14:59.349 --> 00:15:01.640
But also realize that you're
going to have difficulties

00:15:01.640 --> 00:15:02.240
along the way.

00:15:02.240 --> 00:15:05.560
And in this case, my biggest
difficulty, my biggest,

00:15:05.560 --> 00:15:10.210
loudest heckler, the most
miserable day of my life

00:15:10.210 --> 00:15:13.519
was on, I believe,
March 2, 2013.

00:15:13.519 --> 00:15:15.810
How many of you guys are
familiar with the online forum

00:15:15.810 --> 00:15:16.512
4chan?

00:15:16.512 --> 00:15:17.220
Hands in the air?

00:15:17.220 --> 00:15:20.160
OK They have a bit of a
reputation, those guys.

00:15:23.620 --> 00:15:29.280
One day 4chan says, hey,
let's roll some dice

00:15:29.280 --> 00:15:33.730
and whoever they
roll up on, let's all

00:15:33.730 --> 00:15:35.700
rush that person's
YouTube channel

00:15:35.700 --> 00:15:39.230
and accuse that person
of being a pedophile.

00:15:39.230 --> 00:15:41.560
Which, I'm not going to
lie, it's kind of brilliant.

00:15:41.560 --> 00:15:44.622
Because it's, literally,
it's the perfect box.

00:15:44.622 --> 00:15:46.580
You rush in, and you call
somebody a pedophile,

00:15:46.580 --> 00:15:47.704
what are they going to say?

00:15:47.704 --> 00:15:49.900
No, I love children!

00:15:49.900 --> 00:15:51.400
I have children!

00:15:51.400 --> 00:15:53.350
Why would you say that?

00:15:53.350 --> 00:15:56.550
One of the many sayings
associated with 4chan

00:15:56.550 --> 00:15:59.020
is that they do stuff
for the lulz, meaning,

00:15:59.020 --> 00:16:00.110
it's not personal.

00:16:00.110 --> 00:16:01.250
We don't actually hate you.

00:16:01.250 --> 00:16:02.190
We could care less.

00:16:02.190 --> 00:16:04.050
We just want to get a
chuckle out of this.

00:16:04.050 --> 00:16:07.240
So we'll ruin your life.

00:16:07.240 --> 00:16:10.235
And so, sure enough,
that day-- luckily, they

00:16:10.235 --> 00:16:11.860
had grabbed screen shots of it.

00:16:11.860 --> 00:16:13.986
But apparently they
were like, hey,

00:16:13.986 --> 00:16:16.360
whose life should we ruin with
accusations of pedophilia?

00:16:16.360 --> 00:16:18.600
Somebody was like, how
about Justin Bieber?

00:16:18.600 --> 00:16:19.930
Well, let's roll the dice.

00:16:19.930 --> 00:16:21.640
No, it's not going
to be Justin Bieber.

00:16:21.640 --> 00:16:22.260
What about this guy?

00:16:22.260 --> 00:16:23.660
He does science
demos on YouTube.

00:16:23.660 --> 00:16:24.810
Well, let's roll the dice.

00:16:24.810 --> 00:16:25.730
No, it won't be him.

00:16:25.730 --> 00:16:27.730
And then somebody was
like, what about this guy?

00:16:27.730 --> 00:16:30.310
He does magic on the internet.

00:16:30.310 --> 00:16:33.230
[SOUND EFFECT] We have a winner!

00:16:33.230 --> 00:16:39.840
And I got a-- yeah, we'll do
this-- I got a tweet saying,

00:16:39.840 --> 00:16:42.210
heads up, 4chan raid incoming.

00:16:42.210 --> 00:16:44.600
And I went and checked
out our most recent video,

00:16:44.600 --> 00:16:47.010
and there was a bit of
a traffic spike on it.

00:16:47.010 --> 00:16:50.882
And all of it being nothing but
everything you would imagine.

00:16:50.882 --> 00:16:52.340
Like, oh my gosh,
you can't believe

00:16:52.340 --> 00:16:53.670
what this guy did to that girl.

00:16:53.670 --> 00:16:54.545
I can't believe this.

00:16:54.545 --> 00:16:56.290
Oh, I used to respect this guy!

00:16:56.290 --> 00:16:57.910
I hope he rots in hell!

00:16:57.910 --> 00:17:01.420
And you could see that it
was very clearly coordinated,

00:17:01.420 --> 00:17:03.140
and it was rolling outward.

00:17:03.140 --> 00:17:05.230
Because first it was
just the one video.

00:17:05.230 --> 00:17:07.680
Then it was the next
video next door.

00:17:07.680 --> 00:17:12.000
Then it was my Wikipedia
page getting vandalized.

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:15.050
And luckily, I happen to be
in the middle of a recording

00:17:15.050 --> 00:17:17.770
session with my co-host,
Justin Robert Young.

00:17:17.770 --> 00:17:19.380
We were recording
a comedy album.

00:17:19.380 --> 00:17:21.169
And I was like, what do you do?

00:17:21.169 --> 00:17:22.210
This is the perfect play.

00:17:22.210 --> 00:17:23.400
This is the perfect troll.

00:17:23.400 --> 00:17:25.130
There is no response.

00:17:25.130 --> 00:17:26.920
And Justin nailed it.

00:17:26.920 --> 00:17:30.860
He says, you have to take
the wind out of their sails.

00:17:30.860 --> 00:17:33.130
Understand they
hold all the power.

00:17:33.130 --> 00:17:34.540
You hold none of it.

00:17:34.540 --> 00:17:38.170
The only thing you can
do is make it not fun

00:17:38.170 --> 00:17:40.860
for them to continue
going forward.

00:17:40.860 --> 00:17:42.560
And so we poked
around a little bit.

00:17:42.560 --> 00:17:44.980
We knew that, what does
the internet respond to?

00:17:44.980 --> 00:17:46.080
They respond to effort.

00:17:46.080 --> 00:17:48.180
They respond to honesty.

00:17:48.180 --> 00:17:49.510
They responded directness.

00:17:49.510 --> 00:17:51.770
They respond to respect.

00:17:51.770 --> 00:17:53.957
And what we ended up
doing-- I hope I'm still

00:17:53.957 --> 00:17:55.040
connected to the internet.

00:17:55.040 --> 00:17:59.390
I was going to-- let me see
if I can throw this on here.

00:17:59.390 --> 00:18:02.590
You guys can not
see that apparently.

00:18:02.590 --> 00:18:03.700
There we go.

00:18:03.700 --> 00:18:06.520
So, this is an
advertisement that I'm going

00:18:06.520 --> 00:18:09.970
