00:22:06.280 --> 00:22:08.370
being regular
content once a week,

00:22:08.370 --> 00:22:11.020
and we have two spin off
shows behind the Scam

00:22:11.020 --> 00:22:15.660
and "Scam School" remix
that along with partnerships

00:22:15.660 --> 00:22:19.160
for promotions, we're able to
get enough to keep like a three

00:22:19.160 --> 00:22:21.460
man team sustained.

00:22:21.460 --> 00:22:23.669
Where it's worth it to
invest the time to do it.

00:22:23.669 --> 00:22:25.460
I don't know if that
answers your question.

00:22:25.460 --> 00:22:27.100
But we're finally
to a point where

00:22:27.100 --> 00:22:28.474
the pie is big
enough that we can

00:22:28.474 --> 00:22:30.600
support three people full time.

00:22:30.600 --> 00:22:33.980
And that ended up being
three videos per week,

00:22:33.980 --> 00:22:38.130
and we're hoping to expand
even more from there.

00:22:38.130 --> 00:22:40.810
Any other questions?

00:22:40.810 --> 00:22:45.360
AUDIENCE: How about what--
are there any new platforms,

00:22:45.360 --> 00:22:51.580
after YouTube Launch, that you
think are good places to be bad

00:22:51.580 --> 00:22:53.150
so that you can become good?

00:22:53.150 --> 00:22:54.025
BRIAN BUSHWOOD: Yeah.

00:22:54.025 --> 00:22:57.020
Nowadays, I would say Periscope
is a fantastic-- or Meerkat.

00:22:57.020 --> 00:22:59.740
Basically, in many ways,
what we're seeing right now

00:22:59.740 --> 00:23:03.570
is a reboot of what we saw
in the live stream space

00:23:03.570 --> 00:23:04.930
exactly six years ago.

00:23:04.930 --> 00:23:08.140
It used to be that
Ustream and Justin.tv were

00:23:08.140 --> 00:23:09.980
the big, easy ways to jump in.

00:23:09.980 --> 00:23:12.520
And nowadays, that's
kind of come full circle,

00:23:12.520 --> 00:23:14.160
and nowadays you have
it on your phone.

00:23:14.160 --> 00:23:17.260
And so it's amazing
what happens-- like,

00:23:17.260 --> 00:23:18.885
right now, I'm
looking at you guys.

00:23:18.885 --> 00:23:19.760
You're looking at me.

00:23:19.760 --> 00:23:20.980
This is a very real moment.

00:23:20.980 --> 00:23:23.630
I'm 100% dialed in and present.

00:23:23.630 --> 00:23:25.410
It's amazing what
happens when you

00:23:25.410 --> 00:23:28.460
watch that viewer count
rise up in front of you

00:23:28.460 --> 00:23:29.942
because you can
picture the room.

00:23:29.942 --> 00:23:31.400
And it's like, I
know what it looks

00:23:31.400 --> 00:23:34.770
like to perform for 30 to 40
people at a time in a room.

00:23:34.770 --> 00:23:38.020
And when whenever I see
currently watching 30 to 40,

00:23:38.020 --> 00:23:39.810
I picture exactly that room.

00:23:39.810 --> 00:23:43.160
And I picture trying to hold
everybody's interest exactly

00:23:43.160 --> 00:23:43.880
that hard.

00:23:43.880 --> 00:23:45.900
Puts you in a totally
different head space.

00:23:45.900 --> 00:23:48.560
So I would say, definitely,
a safe place to be bad.

00:23:48.560 --> 00:23:51.390
Especially because
Meerkat, Periscope only

00:23:51.390 --> 00:23:53.270
gets saved if you
want to be saved.

00:23:53.270 --> 00:23:55.990
And that's a precious and
rare commodity nowadays.

00:23:55.990 --> 00:23:56.950
Yeah.

00:23:56.950 --> 00:23:58.940
AUDIENCE: After the four
and half page response

00:23:58.940 --> 00:24:01.040
from Teller, did you
ever have an opportunity

00:24:01.040 --> 00:24:03.259
to get into another
conversation with him?

00:24:03.259 --> 00:24:04.425
Like what was that response?

00:24:04.425 --> 00:24:05.300
BRIAN BUSHWOOD: Yeah.

00:24:05.300 --> 00:24:09.350
As a matter of fact, was
astonishing because, like I

00:24:09.350 --> 00:24:11.360
said, just writing the
letter meant a lot to me.

00:24:11.360 --> 00:24:14.610
But instead, you get this
extraordinary journey

00:24:14.610 --> 00:24:18.000
about how-- one of
the things he says

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:21.194
in there is at the heart of
all great magic is surprise.

00:24:21.194 --> 00:24:22.860
And the way he phrased
it was beautiful.

00:24:22.860 --> 00:24:24.990
He said, put two and
two in front of me,

00:24:24.990 --> 00:24:28.500
convince me it's five, then
reveal the truth, four,

00:24:28.500 --> 00:24:30.490
and blow me away.

00:24:30.490 --> 00:24:33.500
It ended up kicking
off a correspondence.

00:24:33.500 --> 00:24:36.470
Every time I had a new routine,
I would record VHS tapes,

00:24:36.470 --> 00:24:38.314
back in the day,
and mail them over.

00:24:38.314 --> 00:24:40.980
And I was always astonished that
he took the time to watch them,

00:24:40.980 --> 00:24:43.110
and he gave
thoughtful responses.

00:24:43.110 --> 00:24:47.830
As a matter of fact, I recently
was on Penn and Teller's show,

00:24:47.830 --> 00:24:50.960
"Fool Us" and a bunch of
people were a little bit

00:24:50.960 --> 00:24:54.610
dis-- I would say, some
fans were disappointed

00:24:54.610 --> 00:24:58.940
because they wanted me to try
harder to fool Penn and Teller.

00:24:58.940 --> 00:25:02.130
And what I couldn't
really say to most of them

00:25:02.130 --> 00:25:05.570
was that-- Fool Us
Brian Brushwood.

00:25:05.570 --> 00:25:06.070
Here we go.

00:25:06.070 --> 00:25:08.750
What I couldn't
say is that I don't

00:25:08.750 --> 00:25:13.590
think there's a single
stage act in my entire show

00:25:13.590 --> 00:25:16.350
that Teller hasn't had a
personal hand in helping

00:25:16.350 --> 00:25:17.160
me write.

00:25:17.160 --> 00:25:20.820
Whether it's giving
feedback or giving

00:25:20.820 --> 00:25:25.700
an interpretation or an
unusual theatrical spin on.

00:25:25.700 --> 00:25:27.814
So it occurred to
me that if I was not

00:25:27.814 --> 00:25:30.230
going to fool Penn and Teller--
because you can't fool dad

00:25:30.230 --> 00:25:33.450
when he taught you everything
you know-- what I was going

00:25:33.450 --> 00:25:36.780
to do was play to the audience
and instead figure out

00:25:36.780 --> 00:25:41.200
how to find moments of-- to step
outside the rules for any given

00:25:41.200 --> 00:25:41.720
performance.

00:25:41.720 --> 00:25:44.670
So in this case, what I did
was we took a bill from the guy

00:25:44.670 --> 00:25:45.420
from the audience.

00:25:45.420 --> 00:25:47.179
We chopped it up.

00:25:47.179 --> 00:25:48.720
And again, this is
not rocket science

00:25:48.720 --> 00:25:49.910
from a magic perspective.

00:25:49.910 --> 00:25:51.780
But what I love
about this routine

00:25:51.780 --> 00:25:56.360
is that I actually make an
individual from the audience

00:25:56.360 --> 00:26:00.550
eat the burnt ashes of his
own selected signed bill.

00:26:00.550 --> 00:26:01.830
And there is no trick.

00:26:01.830 --> 00:26:05.234
It is all designed to take
advantage of social pressure.

00:26:05.234 --> 00:26:06.900
The first thing I say
is, I need someone

00:26:06.900 --> 00:26:10.240
from the audience who's willing
to do absolutely anything.

00:26:10.240 --> 00:26:13.830
And whoever stands up and goes,
whoop, then it's like you,

00:26:13.830 --> 00:26:14.810
get on up here.

00:26:14.810 --> 00:26:17.050
And then, we have
him select the bill.

00:26:17.050 --> 00:26:18.350
We burn it up.

00:26:18.350 --> 00:26:19.870
And then I chop
it up and I mix it

00:26:19.870 --> 00:26:21.950
with his choice, either
applesauce or pudding.

00:26:21.950 --> 00:26:24.020
So he now has a
small investment.

00:26:24.020 --> 00:26:25.980
And as I'm mixing,
there's this great moment

00:26:25.980 --> 00:26:27.460
that I say, hey, do me a favor.

00:26:27.460 --> 00:26:28.090
Just taste it.

00:26:28.090 --> 00:26:28.700
Just taste it.

00:26:28.700 --> 00:26:30.658
Again, I'm not asking
him to do anything crazy.

00:26:30.658 --> 00:26:31.790
I say, just taste this.

00:26:31.790 --> 00:26:34.150
So now he's tasted
it, and he's on stage

00:26:34.150 --> 00:26:36.970
and all of a sudden, that's
when it's like checkmate.

00:26:36.970 --> 00:26:38.840
Then I'm like, do me a favor.

00:26:38.840 --> 00:26:39.870
Just polish this off.

00:26:39.870 --> 00:26:41.780
Something amazing
is going to happen.

00:26:41.780 --> 00:26:44.800
The faster you eat, the
louder they're going to clap.

00:26:44.800 --> 00:26:45.630
Watch.

00:26:45.630 --> 00:26:47.960
And then all of a sudden,
the audience is cheering,

00:26:47.960 --> 00:26:50.270
and he realizes that there's
no getting out of this.

00:26:50.270 --> 00:26:51.410
And he actually does it.

00:26:51.410 --> 00:26:54.520
And then we go on
to pull them apart.

00:26:54.520 --> 00:26:56.520
But again, the
whole reason that I

00:26:56.520 --> 00:27:00.490
wanted to do this particular
routine was not to fool.

00:27:00.490 --> 00:27:04.380
People think that the power
in magic is in the mystery

00:27:04.380 --> 00:27:09.850
or in the gap of me knowing
how it's done and you not.

00:27:09.850 --> 00:27:12.350
That could not be farther
from the truth, in my opinion.

00:27:12.350 --> 00:27:15.590
There is no mystery when
we watch a concert pianist.

00:27:15.590 --> 00:27:17.300
We know exactly
what's happening.

00:27:17.300 --> 00:27:21.920
They press the key a hammer
strikes a wire that's

00:27:21.920 --> 00:27:23.270
tuned to a frequency.

00:27:23.270 --> 00:27:26.900
And he just does all of it in
an exquisitely beautiful, heart

00:27:26.900 --> 00:27:29.180
wrenching, tear
inducing symphony.

00:27:29.180 --> 00:27:31.410
Right?

00:27:31.410 --> 00:27:32.790
Magic is the same thing.

00:27:32.790 --> 00:27:36.290
If anybody loved magic
as much as I love magic,

00:27:36.290 --> 00:27:38.580
and they knew just
as much as I did,

00:27:38.580 --> 00:27:41.340
then all that
means is that magic

00:27:41.340 --> 00:27:43.850
would become the number
one art on the planet

00:27:43.850 --> 00:27:46.120
and the most popular
thing for everyone to do.

00:27:46.120 --> 00:27:47.810
I think I may have
talked a little bit

00:27:47.810 --> 00:27:49.050
around your question.

00:27:49.050 --> 00:27:51.500
But I hope I got--
the answer is yes.

00:27:51.500 --> 00:27:54.682
Teller and I have had
an exquisite journey

00:27:54.682 --> 00:27:55.390
over these years.

00:27:55.390 --> 00:27:56.931
This correspondence
has been amazing,

00:27:56.931 --> 00:28:00.580
and I hope to get to
share more of that stuff.

00:28:00.580 --> 00:28:03.210
Any other questions?

00:28:03.210 --> 00:28:06.470
AUDIENCE: I'll do
one on "Scam School."

00:28:06.470 --> 00:28:10.410
Which episode would you say was
the one you're most proud of?

00:28:10.410 --> 00:28:13.010
And which one would you say
was the most fun to make?

00:28:13.010 --> 00:28:14.580
Maybe that's the same one.

00:28:14.580 --> 00:28:17.020
BRIAN BUSHWOOD: No, they're
definitely not the same one.

00:28:17.020 --> 00:28:19.750
In fact, the one I'm most
proud of was in every way

00:28:19.750 --> 00:28:22.710
the most miserable one to make.

00:28:22.710 --> 00:28:24.530
But I'm most proud
of it because it

00:28:24.530 --> 00:28:27.590
got performed on the
International Space Station

00:28:27.590 --> 00:28:30.430
by video game legend
Richard Garriott, a.k.a.

00:28:30.430 --> 00:28:32.360
Lord British.

00:28:32.360 --> 00:28:34.920
Turns out Richard Garriott
lives here in Austin.

00:28:34.920 --> 00:28:37.590
As a kid, I was a tremendous
fan of his Ultima series.

00:28:37.590 --> 00:28:39.340
You know, "Ultima III:
Exodus," playing it

00:28:39.340 --> 00:28:40.990
when I was in third grade.

00:28:40.990 --> 00:28:44.960
And I had an idea
for a magic routine

00:28:44.960 --> 00:28:49.270
that you could use YouTube
as a method for the trick.

00:28:49.270 --> 00:28:54.650
So what we did was we recorded
104 different versions

00:28:54.650 --> 00:28:57.710
of a fake interview on YouTube.

00:28:57.710 --> 00:29:00.110
And you guys can
still look this up.

00:29:00.110 --> 00:29:02.430
In fact, we should probably
do a re-mix episode on it.

00:29:02.430 --> 00:29:05.410
But what happens is you
say to someone like,

00:29:05.410 --> 00:29:08.150
hey, I don't know if you
believe in mind control,

00:29:08.150 --> 00:29:10.731
not like this crazy
like voodoo stuff.

00:29:10.731 --> 00:29:11.980
In fact, we'll do it with you.

00:29:11.980 --> 00:29:13.229
What's your name?

00:29:13.229 --> 00:29:13.770
Suzie, Suzie.

00:29:13.770 --> 00:29:14.810
OK.

00:29:14.810 --> 00:29:17.160
I don't believe in ESP or
mind-reading and stuff,

00:29:17.160 --> 00:29:19.100
but I do believe
that there's ways

00:29:19.100 --> 00:29:22.442
to kind of psychologically nudge
people in the right direction.

00:29:22.442 --> 00:29:23.650
And I was watching this show.

00:29:23.650 --> 00:29:25.150
There was this interview.

00:29:25.150 --> 00:29:28.840
There is this crazy
life coach doctor expert

00:29:28.840 --> 00:29:31.790
who said that he
could cause someone

00:29:31.790 --> 00:29:35.030
to think of a playing
card by reciting

00:29:35.030 --> 00:29:36.980
a couple of lines of poetry.

00:29:36.980 --> 00:29:39.070
Let me give this a try.

00:29:39.070 --> 00:29:42.360
The poetry was, "The woods
are lovely, dark, and deep,

00:29:42.360 --> 00:29:48.370
but I have promises to keep and
miles to go before I sleep."

00:29:48.370 --> 00:29:52.620
What playing card are you
thinking of right now?

00:29:52.620 --> 00:29:54.471
AUDIENCE: Eight of clubs.

00:29:54.471 --> 00:29:55.470
BRIAN BUSHWOOD: Shut up.

00:29:55.470 --> 00:29:58.300
Did you see the interview?

00:29:58.300 --> 00:29:59.350
Pinky promise?

00:29:59.350 --> 00:30:03.010
OK, because that's
exactly what the guy says!

00:30:03.010 --> 00:30:04.310
Here, I don't want to touch it.

00:30:04.310 --> 00:30:04.920
I don't want to do it.

00:30:04.920 --> 00:30:07.490
Walk over that computer-- you
don't have to actually do it.

00:30:07.490 --> 00:30:12.860
This guy's name was--
he was a life coach.

00:30:12.860 --> 00:30:17.080
If you search for Coach
Charles Doubleday.

00:30:17.080 --> 00:30:22.889
Here, so you search you go
Coach Charles Doubleday.

00:30:22.889 --> 00:30:24.930
And let's see if we can
find the-- oh good, yeah,

00:30:24.930 --> 00:30:26.010
no here he is.

00:30:26.010 --> 00:30:26.510
Here.

00:30:26.510 --> 00:30:27.010
Look.

00:30:27.010 --> 00:30:29.584
This is the exact interview
I was talking about.

00:30:29.584 --> 00:30:30.250
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:30:30.250 --> 00:30:46.242
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:30:46.242 --> 00:30:47.450
-Welcome back to Scam School.

00:30:47.450 --> 00:30:49.840
We are here at the Nomad
Bar in Austin, Texas.

00:30:49.840 --> 00:30:52.910
And today we are talking
to Coach Charles Doubleday.

00:30:52.910 --> 00:30:54.847
Now before I went to
break, you said something

00:30:54.847 --> 00:30:55.930
that kind of blew my mind.

00:30:55.930 --> 00:30:58.080
It sounded like you were
describing like-- I mean,

00:30:58.080 --> 00:30:59.910
it sound like mind control.

00:30:59.910 --> 00:31:01.530
-Actually it is.

00:31:01.530 --> 00:31:03.280
Our studies of
neurolinguistic programming

00:31:03.280 --> 00:31:05.480
have discovered deep
structures in the human brain

00:31:05.480 --> 00:31:08.710
that can be accessed
with linguistic triggers.

00:31:08.710 --> 00:31:11.970
We can actually put a
thought into someone's mind.

00:31:11.970 --> 00:31:13.810
-Like against their will, yeah?

00:31:13.810 --> 00:31:15.290
Do you any examples?

00:31:15.290 --> 00:31:18.260
-We would read a
poem by Robert Frost.

00:31:18.260 --> 00:31:20.040
"The woods are lovely,
dark, and deep,

00:31:20.040 --> 00:31:23.030
and I have promises to keep and
miles to go before I sleep."

00:31:23.030 --> 00:31:25.210
Then we would have
them think of a card,

00:31:25.210 --> 00:31:28.532
and every time they would
think of the eight of clubs.

00:31:28.532 --> 00:31:29.365
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:31:29.365 --> 00:31:32.920
BRIAN BUSHWOOD: [LAUGHING] So,
one of the beautiful things

00:31:32.920 --> 00:31:36.280
was it turns out that Richard
Garriott was a fan of the show,

00:31:36.280 --> 00:31:40.080
and he found himself in a
quarantine in I want to say,

00:31:40.080 --> 00:31:41.620
Baikonur, Kazahstan.

00:31:41.620 --> 00:31:47.530
And he decided like, wow, this
would be the perfect thing

00:31:47.530 --> 00:31:50.899
to do from a very
remote connection,

00:31:50.899 --> 00:31:52.440
from the International
Space Station,

00:31:52.440 --> 00:31:53.480
and he performed it on his dad.

00:31:53.480 --> 00:31:54.670
And we have that on there.

00:31:54.670 --> 00:31:57.540
Unfortunately, because it
was such a pain in the ass

00:31:57.540 --> 00:32:00.465
to edit together 104 versions
because we wanted to make sure

00:32:00.465 --> 00:32:02.340
there was a long version
and a short version.

00:32:02.340 --> 00:32:05.940
We also had to open up
52 different accounts

00:32:05.940 --> 00:32:09.046
for all of the variations
of the expert's name.

00:32:09.046 --> 00:32:11.670
But the beautiful thing is that
it's a gift that just lives out

00:32:11.670 --> 00:32:13.140
there, all on its own.

00:32:13.140 --> 00:32:15.530
So the answer to your
question is the one

00:32:15.530 --> 00:32:20.690
I'm most proud of was not at all
the most fun to do, in any way.

00:32:20.690 --> 00:32:22.410
Any other questions?

00:32:22.410 --> 00:32:25.679
I know that we're a
little bit tight today.

00:32:25.679 --> 00:32:26.980
Dude.

00:32:26.980 --> 00:32:28.870
Well, if that's it.

